<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!--
IMU Sensor Configuration for Chapter 3: Simulating Sensors
Purpose: Add Inertial Measurement Unit to humanoid robot
Compatible: Gazebo Classic 11, ROS 2 Humble
Sensor Model: Bosch BMI088 6-axis IMU (parameters from datasheet)
-->
<robot xmlns:xacro="http://www.ros.org/wiki/xacro">

  <!-- IMU Link (Physical Sensor Mount - typically small PCB) -->
  <link name="imu_link">
    <visual>
      <origin xyz="0 0 0" rpy="0 0 0"/>
      <geometry>
        <box size="0.01 0.01 0.005"/> <!-- 1cm x 1cm x 0.5cm PCB -->
      </geometry>
      <material name="imu_green">
        <color rgba="0.0 0.6 0.0 1.0"/> <!-- Green PCB -->
      </material>
    </visual>

    <collision>
      <origin xyz="0 0 0" rpy="0 0 0"/>
      <geometry>
        <box size="0.01 0.01 0.005"/>
      </geometry>
    </collision>

    <inertial>
      <mass value="0.005"/> <!-- 5 grams -->
      <origin xyz="0 0 0" rpy="0 0 0"/>
      <inertia ixx="0.000001" ixy="0.0" ixz="0.0" iyy="0.000001" iyz="0.0" izz="0.000001"/>
    </inertial>
  </link>

  <!-- Joint Connecting IMU to Robot Base (typically torso or base_link) -->
  <joint name="imu_joint" type="fixed">
    <parent link="torso_link"/> <!-- Change to base_link or torso_link -->
    <child link="imu_link"/>
    <origin xyz="0.0 0.0 0.05" rpy="0 0 0"/> <!-- 5cm above torso center -->
  </joint>

  <!-- Gazebo IMU Plugin -->
  <gazebo reference="imu_link">
    <sensor name="imu_sensor" type="imu">
      <!-- Update rate (Hz) - High frequency for control loops -->
      <update_rate>100.0</update_rate>

      <!-- Always on (no activation condition) -->
      <always_on>true</always_on>

      <!-- IMU Plugin Configuration -->
      <plugin name="gazebo_ros_imu_sensor" filename="libgazebo_ros_imu_sensor.so">
        <ros>
          <namespace>/robot</namespace>
          <remapping>~/out:=imu/data</remapping> <!-- Publishes to /robot/imu/data -->
        </ros>

        <!-- TF frame for sensor data -->
        <frame_name>imu_link</frame_name>

        <!-- Initial Orientation Reference -->
        <!-- false: Orientation relative to world frame (gravity in Z) -->
        <!-- true: Orientation relative to initial sensor pose -->
        <initial_orientation_as_reference>false</initial_orientation_as_reference>

        <!-- Noise Models (from Bosch BMI088 Datasheet) -->

        <!-- Angular Velocity Noise (Gyroscope) -->
        <!-- Datasheet: 0.014 rad/s/√Hz at 100 Hz -->
        <angular_velocity_stdev>0.014</angular_velocity_stdev> <!-- rad/s -->

        <!-- Linear Acceleration Noise (Accelerometer) -->
        <!-- Datasheet: 150 μg/√Hz ≈ 0.05 m/s²/√Hz at 100 Hz -->
        <linear_acceleration_stdev>0.05</linear_acceleration_stdev> <!-- m/s² -->

        <!-- Orientation Noise (Sensor Fusion Output) -->
        <!-- Computed from gyro integration: ~0.01 rad -->
        <orientation_stdev>0.01</orientation_stdev> <!-- radians -->
      </plugin>
    </sensor>
  </gazebo>

  <!-- Usage Instructions:

  1. Include in main robot URDF:
     <xacro:include filename="imu_sensor.urdf.xacro"/>

  2. Update parent link:
     Change <parent link="torso_link"/> to robot base or torso

  3. Adjust mounting position:
     Mount IMU close to center of mass for accurate acceleration measurements

  4. Launch Gazebo:
     ros2 launch your_package gazebo.launch.py

  5. Verify topic publishing:
     ros2 topic hz /robot/imu/data
     # Expected: average rate: 100.000 Hz

  6. Check IMU output:
     ros2 topic echo /robot/imu/data --once
     # Expected fields:
     # - orientation: Quaternion (x, y, z, w) - robot attitude
     # - angular_velocity: Vector3 (x, y, z) rad/s - rotation rates
     # - linear_acceleration: Vector3 (x, y, z) m/s² - includes gravity (z ≈ 9.81 when stationary)

  Expected Output:
  - Topic: /robot/imu/data (sensor_msgs/Imu)
  - Update rate: 100 Hz
  - Orientation: Quaternion with norm ≈ 1.0 (valid quaternion)
  - Angular velocity: Near zero when robot not rotating
  - Linear acceleration Z: ≈ 9.81 m/s² when stationary (gravity)

  Validation:
  - Orientation accuracy: Compare to known robot pose from /tf
  - Gyro noise: Record 1000 samples when stationary, compute std dev, should match 0.014 rad/s
  - Accel noise: Record 1000 samples, std dev should match 0.05 m/s²

  Troubleshooting:
  - No data published: Check plugin libgazebo_ros_imu_sensor.so exists
    Verify: ls /opt/ros/humble/lib/libgazebo_ros_imu_sensor.so

  - Orientation quaternion invalid (norm ≠ 1.0): Numerical integration error
    Solution: Reduce Gazebo timestep to 0.001s or lower

  - Linear acceleration Z ≠ 9.81 when stationary: Gravity direction wrong
    Solution: Check Gazebo world <gravity>0 0 -9.81</gravity> (Z-axis up)

  - Gyro drifts over time: Bias instability (realistic for MEMS IMU)
    Solution: Use robot_localization package for sensor fusion with wheel odometry

  - High noise (σ > configured): Gazebo simulation timestep too large
    Solution: Reduce <max_step_size> in world file to 0.001s or 0.0005s

  IMU Coordinate Frame Convention (ROS REP-103):
  - X-axis: Forward
  - Y-axis: Left
  - Z-axis: Up
  Gravity vector appears as linear_acceleration.z = 9.81 m/s² when robot stationary.

  Sensor Fusion Note:
  This IMU plugin outputs orientation (from Gazebo's ground truth) + noisy angular velocity + noisy acceleration.
  For realistic IMU behavior (orientation from gyro integration), consider using ADIS16448 plugin or custom EKF.

  -->

</robot>
